        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-4 leading-tight">Fire Extinguisher Inspection in Buffalo, NY: What Every Business Owner Needs to Know</h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-8">If you own or manage a commercial property in Buffalo, NY, your fire extinguishers are a legal requirement with specific inspection schedules enforced by the Buffalo Fire Department. Here's exactly what NFPA 10 and the New York State Uniform Fire Code require, what inspections cost, and how to avoid violations.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3">Buffalo Fire Extinguisher Inspection Requirements</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">The City of Buffalo enforces the New York State Uniform Fire Code, requiring all commercial properties to maintain portable fire extinguishers in compliance with <a href="/compliance/nfpa-10/" class="text-red-brand hover:underline">NFPA 10: Standard for Portable Fire Extinguishers</a>. Four inspection intervals apply to every commercial extinguisher.</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Buffalo's commercial landscape includes the Elmwood Village and Allentown arts and dining districts, the Larkinville innovation district, the Downtown theater corridor, and significant industrial and warehouse operations near the Buffalo waterfront. Buffalo's lake-effect snow and sub-zero winters create specific fire extinguisher maintenance challenges — units stored in unheated spaces risk pressure changes, and corrosion from road salt-laden air affects mounting hardware.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Monthly Visual Inspections</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Monthly visual inspections can be performed by your own trained building staff — no license required. Verify each extinguisher is in its designated location, unobstructed, the pressure gauge reads in the operating range, the tamper seal is intact, and the pull pin is in place. Document every monthly check. In the event of a fire incident or an enforcement action, the absence of monthly records significantly increases your liability exposure.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Annual Professional Inspections</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Annual inspections must be performed by a licensed fire protection technician who inspects mechanical parts, agent condition, pressure gauge, hose and nozzle integrity, and overall unit condition — then attaches a dated service tag. New York State requires fire extinguisher service contractors to hold licensing under the New York State Uniform Fire Prevention and Building Code. The NYS OFPC (518-474-6746) oversees statewide contractor compliance. Note that the NY State Uniform Fire Code differs from the IFC used in most other states — verify your service provider is familiar with NY-specific requirements. Any unit that fails must be immediately serviced, recharged, or replaced.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">6-Year Internal Examination</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Every six years, stored-pressure extinguishers must be emptied, disassembled, and internally examined for corrosion and agent degradation that external inspections miss. This typically includes a complete recharge. Missing the 6-year exam is a frequently cited violation during Buffalo Fire Department commercial property inspections.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">12-Year Hydrostatic Testing</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">At 12 years, extinguisher cylinders must undergo hydrostatic pressure testing to verify structural integrity. Units that fail must be condemned. After passing, units are recharged and marked with the new test date. Plan for some units to require replacement at the 12-year mark — budget accordingly.</p>

