        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3 mt-8">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="flex flex-col gap-4 mb-8"><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">How often do fire extinguishers need to be inspected in Buffalo, NY?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">In Buffalo, NY, fire extinguishers require monthly visual inspections (performed by building staff), annual professional inspections by a licensed technician, 6-year internal examinations, and 12-year hydrostatic testing per NFPA 10 and the New York State Uniform Fire Code.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">How much does a fire extinguisher inspection cost in Buffalo, NY?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Annual fire extinguisher inspections in the Buffalo metro typically cost $16–$40 per unit. 6-year internal examinations run $26–$58 per unit. 12-year hydrostatic testing costs $32–$72 per unit. Volume discounts are available for properties with 20 or more extinguishers.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">Who can inspect fire extinguishers in Buffalo, NY?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Monthly visual checks can be performed by trained building staff. Annual inspections, 6-year internals, and 12-year hydrostatic tests must be performed by a licensed fire protection technician. New York State requires fire extinguisher service contractors to hold licensing under the New York State Uniform Fire Prevention and Building Code. The NYS OFPC (518-474-6746) oversees statewide contractor compliance. Note that the NY State Uniform Fire Code differs from the IFC used in most other states — verify your service provider is familiar with NY-specific requirements.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">What are the penalties for fire extinguisher violations in Buffalo?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">The Buffalo Fire Department issues notices of violation for fire extinguisher deficiencies with correction periods. Uncorrected violations can result in escalating fines. Serious life-safety deficiencies — missing extinguishers, expired tags in high-occupancy areas — face accelerated enforcement timelines.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">Does Buffalo require fire extinguishers in all commercial buildings?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Yes. The New York State Uniform Fire Code requires portable fire extinguishers in all commercial, industrial, and multi-family residential buildings in Buffalo. Type, size, and placement depend on occupancy classification and hazard level as defined by NFPA 10.</p></div></div>

